  "why": "The paper goes beyond merely reporting failing tests by relating failures to model-internal coverage patterns: it defines state- and transition-level coverage over an abstract MDP of RNN states (Section 5) and empirically demonstrates a statistical correlation between state-variation/coverage and transcription errors (WER). However, the analysis remains at the level of model internals and statistical patterns (e.g., Jaccard similarity of covered abstract states vs. WER) and does not trace failures to deeper root causes such as corrupted/biaised training data, spurious features, or concrete vulnerabilities that would suggest specific fixes. Therefore the work provides partial diagnostic insight (linking failures to internals/statistical patterns) but not full explanations of underlying model vulnerabilities.",
  "evidence": "Section 5 (Coverage Criteria) and RQ2/RQ4 analyses: \n- Section 5 (State-/Transition-level coverage): \"Let M = (Sˆ, I, Tˆ) be an abstract model of the trained RNN represented as a MDP... we define both the state-level and transition-level coverage of T to measure how extensively T exercises the states and transitions of M, respectively.\" (Section 5, p. 10-11). \n- Empirical correlation between state variation and errors: \"Answer to RQ 2: There is a strong correlation between the state variation (i.e., the Jaccard Index) and erroneous behaviors of the RNN (i.e., WER). The transformed audio is likely to trigger more erroneous behaviors if it covers more different states comparing with the original audio.\" (Section 7.3, RQ2 Answer, p. 17). \n- Coverage-guided generation yields higher error rates with finer abstractions: \"Answer to RQ 4: DeepCruiser can effectively generate tests to trigger erroneous behaviors of the RNN. For more fine-grained abstract model, it will capture more erroneous behaviors (i.e., higher WER) of the RNN.\" (Section 7.5, RQ4 Answer, p. 19). \n- Figures/Tables supporting the above: \"Fig. 7: Correlation between basic state variation and relative WER under different abstraction configurations.\" and \"Fig. 8: Average WER of inputs generated with DeepCruiser.\" (Section 7, pp. 16-19). \nNo diagnostic claims linking failures to training-data corruption, dataset bias, spurious features, or concrete mitigation strategies are presented (e.g., no sections or quotes tracing failures to such root causes)."
